As far as history goes, there is no single Age of Piracy. Late Republican Rome had trouble with pirates, for instance. A young Julius Caesar was famously captured by them, promising the pirates he'd crucify them. They thought he was funny, and eventually released him. He came back later and crucified them, but also settled the pirates and solved the problem. What makes an age of piracy possible is a surplus of men and ships, and opportunity. Something similar happened in the US with pilots and aircraft after WWI, though sadly no actual sky piracy followed. But pilots did partake in other reckless acts for money, such as barnstorming. Either way, I'd still caution to be aware of available technology, because it's quite important in the context of aircraft. The '30's in real life saw progress of technology that was insane. The US government was ordering replacement designs for aircraft they hadn't even taken into service yet.

Anonymous Sun 20 Nov 2022 04:13:07 No.52472245 Report
Quoted By: >>52472566
>>52471585
I think you are using the verb "to sustain" perhaps grammatically correctly, but unclearly. A word like that implies a starting condition, and without it we don't know what is being sustained. Also, its use in this situation seems fairly archaic and/or British English to me.

My opinion is that you need to focus on use of language and become comfortable writing in English, if that's the way you want to go. Write more, I guess. Read English language books. That's how I learned. For general writing, the first thing I'd do is veer away from greentext style writing. A lot will eventually come down to an instinctive feel of what "feels good", and it's harder to develop that feel if you train yourself to write in disjointed, clipped sentences. English, for all its popularity, is kind of a weird language. Its nearest relative is Frisian. Google The Chaos Poem if you want to see some of the ways English doesn't obey its own rules.

As for the story itself, it could stand to be more descriptive. You know, what does it feel like to dive out of the sun onto the deck trying to hit a tiny target? Do they have to shout at each other over the roar of the engines? Are the controls heavy with only one pilot behind the stick? Give it some flavor, and be aware of the internal logic you build for yourself. For instance, if Elie wants to get a look at the ship behind them, she probably can't do it from the cockpit (even fighters had shit rear-ward vision until bubble canopies became a thing), so she needs to go to another crew position, but then they can't communicate. But you can use that space to give either character internal monologue. You can establish it now, and use it to build tension later (they were shot at, one can't hear the other, and worries they were hit, for instance).

Maybe try rewriting the first bit with this in mind. Instead of telling us who the characters are and what they do, show it through the action and their experiences of it.
